    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning sensation during HIIT sprints is a classic sign of metabolic stress, which involves the buildup of hydrogen ions, often associated with lactic acid, in your muscles. When you push yourself hard, your muscles need energy faster than oxygen can be supplied through aerobic respiration, leading to anaerobic glycolysis. To get rid of this metabolic byproduct, your body employs several mechanisms, like the Cori cycle in the liver, which converts lactate back into glucose. Essentially, your body is working overtime to clear the acidic waste from your hardworking leg muscles.",
      "source": "target",
